# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: databases
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:databases/acid] In computer science, **ACID** (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) is a set of properties of database transactions intended to guarantee data validity despite errors, power failures, and other mishaps.
[src:databases/acid] For example, a transfer of funds from one bank account to another, involving multiple changes such as debiting one account and crediting another, is a single transaction.
[src:databases/acid] In 1983, Andreas Reuter and Theo Härder coined the acronym *ACID*, building on earlier work by Jim Gray who named atomicity, consistency, and durability, but not isolation, when characterizing the transaction concept.
[src:databases/acid] These four properties are the major guarantees of the transaction paradigm, which has influenced many aspects of development in database systems.
[src:databases/acid] According to Gray and Reuter, the IBM Information Management System supported ACID transactions as early as 1973 (although the acronym was created later).
[src:databases/acid] BASE stands for **b**asically **a**vailable, **s**oft state, and **e**ventually consistent: the acronym highlights that BASE is opposite of ACID, like their chemical equivalents, acid and base.
[src:databases/acid] A database either leans towards ACID or BASE, but it cannot be both (according to CAP theorem).
[src:databases/acid] For example, SQL databases (like MySQL, PostgreSQL, AWS RedShift) are structured over the ACID model, while NoSQL databases (like DynamoDB or MongoDB) use the BASE architecture.
[src:databases/acid] However, some NoSQL databases might exhibit certain ACID traits.
[src:databases/acid] Transactions are often composed of multiple statements.
[src:databases/acid] Atomicity guarantees that each transaction is treated as a single "unit", which either succeeds completely or fails completely: if any of the statements constituting a transaction fails to complete, the entire transaction fails and the database is left unchanged.
[src:databases/acid] An atomic system must guarantee atomicity in each and every situation, including power failures, errors, and crashes.
[src:databases/acid] A guarantee of atomicity prevents updates to the database from occurring only partially, which can cause greater problems than rejecting the whole series outright.
[src:databases/acid] As a consequence, the transaction cannot be observed to be in progress by another database client.
[src:databases/acid] At one moment in time, it has not yet happened, and at the next, it has already occurred in whole (or nothing happened if the transaction was cancelled in progress).
[src:databases/acid] Consistency ensures that a transaction can only bring the database from one consistent state to another, preserving database invariants: any data written to the database must be valid according to all defined rules, including constraints, cascades, triggers, and any combination thereof.
[src:databases/acid] This prevents database corruption by an illegal transaction.
[src:databases/acid] An example of a database invariant is referential integrity, which guarantees the primary key–foreign key relationship.
[src:databases/acid] Transactions are often executed concurrently (e.g., multiple transactions reading and writing to a table at the same time).
[src:databases/acid] Isolation ensures that concurrent execution of transactions leaves the database in the same state that would have been obtained if the transactions were executed sequentially.
[src:databases/acid] Isolation is the main goal of concurrency control; depending on the isolation level used, the effects of an incomplete transaction might not be visible to other transactions.
[src:databases/acid] Durability guarantees that once a transaction has been committed, it will remain committed even in the case of a system failure (e.g., power outage or crash).
[src:databases/acid] This usually means that completed transactions (or their effects) are recorded in non-volatile memory.
[src:databases/acid] The following examples further illustrate the ACID properties.
[src:databases/acid] In these examples, the database table has two columns, A and B.
[src:databases/acid] An integrity constraint requires that the value in A and the value in B must sum to 100.
[src:databases/acid] Atomicity is the guarantee that series of database operations in an atomic transaction will either all occur (a successful operation), or none will occur (an unsuccessful operation).
[src:databases/acid] The series of operations cannot be separated with only some of them being executed, which makes the series of operations "indivisible".
[src:databases/acid] In other words, atomicity means indivisibility and irreducibility.
[src:databases/acid] Alternatively, we may say that a logical transaction may be composed of several physical transactions.
[src:databases/acid] Unless and until all component physical transactions are executed, the logical transaction will not have occurred.
[src:databases/acid] An example of an atomic transaction is a monetary transfer from bank account A to account B.
[src:databases/acid] It consists of two operations, withdrawing the money from account A and depositing it to account B.
[src:databases/acid] We would not want to see the amount removed from account A before we are sure it has also been transferred into account B.
[src:databases/acid] Performing these operations in an atomic transaction ensures that the database remains in a consistent state, that is, money is neither debited nor credited if either of those two operations fails.
[src:databases/acid] Consistency is a very general term, which demands that the data must meet all validation rules.
[src:databases/acid] In the previous example, the validation is a requirement that *A* + *B* = 100.
[src:databases/acid] All validation rules must be checked to ensure consistency.
[src:databases/acid] Assume that a transaction attempts to subtract 10 from *A* without altering *B*.
[src:databases/acid] Because consistency is checked after each transaction, it is known that *A* + *B* = 100 before the transaction begins.
[src:databases/acid] If the transaction removes 10 from *A* successfully, atomicity will be achieved.
[src:databases/acid] However, a validation check will show that *A* + *B* = 90, which is inconsistent with the rules of the database.
[src:databases/acid] The entire transaction must be canceled and the affected rows rolled back to their pre-transaction state.
[src:databases/acid] If there had been other constraints, triggers, or cascades, every single change operation would have been checked in the same way as above before the transaction was committed.
[src:databases/acid] Similar issues may arise with other constraints.
[src:databases/acid] We may have required the data types of both *A* and *B* to be integers.
[src:databases/acid] If we were then to enter, say, the value 13.5 for *A*, the transaction will be canceled, or the system may give rise to an alert in the form of a trigger (if/when the trigger has been written to this effect).
[src:databases/acid] Another example would be integrity constraints, which would not allow us to delete a row in one table whose primary key is referred to by at least one foreign key in other tables.
[src:databases/acid] To demonstrate isolation, we assume two transactions execute at the same time, each attempting to modify the same data.
[src:databases/acid] One of the two must wait until the other completes in order to maintain isolation.
[src:databases/acid] If these operations are performed in order, isolation is maintained, although T2 must wait.
[src:databases/acid] Consider what happens if T1 fails halfway through.
[src:databases/acid] The database eliminates T1's effects, and T2 sees only valid data.
[src:databases/acid] Again, consider what happens if T1 fails while modifying B in Step 4.
[src:databases/acid] By the time T1 fails, T2 has already modified A; it cannot be restored to the value it had before T1 without leaving an invalid database.
[src:databases/acid] This is known as a write-write contention, because two transactions attempted to write to the same data field.
[src:databases/acid] In a typical system, the problem would be resolved by reverting to the last known good state, canceling the failed transaction T1, and restarting the interrupted transaction T2 from the good state.
[src:databases/acid] Consider a transaction that transfers 10 from A to B.
[src:databases/acid] First, it removes 10 from A, then it adds 10 to B.
[src:databases/acid] At this point, the user is told the transaction was a success.
[src:databases/acid] However, the changes are still queued in the disk buffer waiting to be committed to disk.
[src:databases/acid] Power fails and the changes are lost, but the user assumes (understandably) that the changes persist.
[src:databases/acid] Processing a transaction often requires a sequence of operations that is subject to failure for a number of reasons.
[src:databases/acid] For instance, the system may have no room left on its disk drives, or it may have used up its allocated CPU time.
[src:databases/acid] There are two popular families of techniques: write-ahead logging and shadow paging.
[src:databases/acid] In both cases, locks must be acquired on all information to be updated, and depending on the level of isolation, possibly on all data that may be read as well.
[src:databases/acid] In write ahead logging, durability is guaranteed by writing the prospective change to a persistent log before changing the database.
[src:databases/acid] That allows the database to return to a consistent state in the event of a crash.
[src:databases/acid] In shadowing, updates are applied to a partial copy of the database, and the new copy is activated when the transaction commits.
[src:databases/acid] Many databases rely upon locking to provide ACID capabilities.
[src:databases/acid] Locking means that the transaction marks the data that it accesses so that the DBMS knows not to allow other transactions to modify it until the first transaction succeeds or fails.
[src:databases/acid] The lock must always be acquired before processing data, including data that is read but not modified.
[src:databases/acid] Non-trivial transactions typically require a large number of locks, resulting in substantial overhead as well as blocking other transactions.
[src:databases/acid] For example, if user A is running a transaction that has to read a row of data that user B wants to modify, user B must wait until user A's transaction completes.
[src:databases/acid] Two-phase locking is often applied to guarantee full isolation.
[src:databases/acid] An alternative to locking is multiversion concurrency control, in which the database provides each reading transaction the prior, unmodified version of data that is being modified by another active transaction.
[src:databases/acid] This allows readers to operate without acquiring locks, i.e., writing transactions do not block reading transactions, and readers do not block writers.
[src:databases/acid] Going back to the example, when user A's transaction requests data that user B is modifying, the database provides A with the version of that data that existed when user B started his transaction.
[src:databases/acid] User A gets a consistent view of the database even if other users are changing data.
[src:databases/acid] One implementation, namely snapshot isolation, relaxes the isolation property.
[src:databases/acid] Guaranteeing ACID properties in a distributed transaction across a distributed database, where no single node is responsible for all data affecting a transaction, presents additional complications.
[src:databases/acid] Network connections might fail, or one node might successfully complete its part of the transaction and then be required to roll back its changes because of a failure on another node.
[src:databases/acid] The two-phase commit protocol (not to be confused with two-phase locking) provides atomicity for distributed transactions to ensure that each participant in the transaction agrees on whether the transaction should be committed or not.
[src:databases/acid] Briefly, in the first phase, one node (the coordinator) interrogates the other nodes (the participants), and only when all reply that they are prepared does the coordinator, in the second phase, formalize the transaction.
[src:databases/b-tree] A **B+ tree** is an m-ary tree with a variable but often large number of children per node.
[src:databases/b-tree] A B+ tree consists of a root, internal nodes, and leaves.
[src:databases/b-tree] The root may be either a leaf or a node with two or more children.
[src:databases/b-tree] A B+ tree can be viewed as a B-tree in which each node contains only keys (not key–value pairs), and to which an additional level is added at the bottom with linked leaves.
[src:databases/b-tree] The primary value of a B+ tree is in storing data for efficient retrieval in a block-oriented storage context—in particular, filesystems.
[src:databases/b-tree] This is primarily because unlike binary search trees, B+ trees have very high fanout (number of pointers to child nodes in a node, typically on the order of 100 or more), which reduces the number of I/O operations required to find an element in the tree.
[src:databases/b-tree] There is no single paper introducing the B+ tree concept.
[src:databases/b-tree] Instead, the notion of maintaining all data in leaf nodes is repeatedly brought up as an interesting variant of the B-tree, which was introduced by R.
[src:databases/b-tree] Douglas Comer notes in an early survey of B-trees (which also covers B+ trees) that the B+ tree was used in IBM's VSAM data access software, and refers to an IBM published article from 1973.
[src:databases/b-tree] As with other trees, B+ trees can be represented as a collection of three types of nodes: *root*, *internal* (a.k.a. interior), and *leaf*.
[src:databases/b-tree] By definition, each value contained within the B+ tree is a key contained in exactly one leaf node.
[src:databases/b-tree] Each key is required to be directly comparable with every other key, which forms a total order.
[src:databases/b-tree] This enables each leaf node to keep all of its keys sorted at all times, which then enables each internal node to construct an ordered collection of intervals representing the contiguous extent of values contained in a given leaf.
[src:databases/b-tree] Internal nodes higher in the tree can then construct their own intervals, which recursively aggregate the intervals contained in their own child internal nodes.
[src:databases/b-tree] Eventually, the root of a B+ Tree represents the whole range of values in the tree, where every internal node represents a subinterval.
[src:databases/b-tree] For this recursive interval information to be retained, internal nodes must additionally contain $m-1$ copies of keys $l_{i}$ for $i\in [1,m-1]$ representing the least element within the interval covered by the child with index i (which may itself be an internal node, or a leaf).
[src:databases/b-tree] Where m represents the *actual* number of children for a given internal node.
[src:databases/b-tree] The *order* or *branching factor* b of a B+ tree measures the capacity of interior nodes, i.e. their maximum allowed number of direct child nodes.
[src:databases/b-tree] This value is constant over the entire tree.
[src:databases/b-tree] We are looking for a value k in the B+ Tree.
[src:databases/b-tree] This means that starting from the root, we are looking for the leaf which may contain the value k.
[src:databases/b-tree] At each node, we figure out which internal node we should follow.
[src:databases/b-tree] An internal B+ Tree node has at most $m\leq b$ children, where every one of them represents a different sub-interval.
[src:databases/b-tree] We select the corresponding child via a linear search of the m entries, then when we finally get to a leaf, we do a linear search of its n elements for the desired key.
[src:databases/b-tree] Because we only traverse one branch of all the children at each rung of the tree, we achieve $O(\log N)$ runtime, where N is the total number of keys stored in the leaves of the B+ tree.
[src:databases/b-tree] Note that this pseudocode uses 1-based array indexing.
[src:databases/b-tree] B+ trees grow at the root and not at the leaves.
[src:databases/b-tree] Given a collection of data records, we want to create a B+ tree index on some key field.
[src:databases/b-tree] One approach is to insert each record into an empty tree.
[src:databases/b-tree] However, it is quite expensive, because each entry requires us to start from the root and go down to the appropriate leaf page.
[src:databases/b-tree] An efficient alternative is to use bulk-loading.
[src:databases/b-tree] The purpose of the delete algorithm is to remove the desired entry node from the tree structure.
[src:databases/b-tree] We recursively call the delete algorithm on the appropriate node until no node is found.
[src:databases/b-tree] For each function call, we traverse along, using the index to navigate until we find the node, remove it, and then work back up to the root.
[src:databases/b-tree] Note: merge could propagate to root, which means decreasing height.
[src:databases/b-tree] The leaves (the bottom-most index blocks) of the B+ tree are often linked to one another in a linked list; this makes range queries or an (ordered) iteration through the blocks simpler and more efficient (though the aforementioned upper bound can be achieved even without this addition).
[src:databases/b-tree] This does not substantially increase space consumption or maintenance on the tree.
[src:databases/b-tree] This illustrates one of the significant advantages of a B+tree over a B-tree; in a B-tree, since not all keys are present in the leaves, such an ordered linked list cannot be constructed.
[src:databases/b-tree] A B+tree is thus particularly useful as a database system index, where the data typically resides on disk, as it allows the B+tree to actually provide an efficient structure for housing the data itself (this is described in as index structure "Alternative 1").
[src:databases/b-tree] If a storage system has a block size of B bytes, and the keys to be stored have a size of k, arguably the most efficient B+ tree is one where $b={\tfrac {B}{k}}-1$ .
[src:databases/b-tree] Although theoretically the one-off is unnecessary, in practice there is often a little extra space taken up by the index blocks (for example, the linked list references in the leaf blocks).
[src:databases/b-tree] Having an index block which is slightly larger than the storage system's actual block represents a significant performance decrease; therefore erring on the side of caution is preferable.
[src:databases/b-tree] If nodes of the B+ tree are organized as arrays of elements, then it may take a considerable time to insert or delete an element as half of the array will need to be shifted on average.
[src:databases/b-tree] To overcome this problem, elements inside a node can be organized in a binary tree or a B+ tree instead of an array.
[src:databases/b-tree] B+ trees can also be used for data stored in RAM.
[src:databases/b-tree] In this case a reasonable choice for block size would be the size of processor's cache line.
[src:databases/b-tree] Space efficiency of B+ trees can be improved by using some compression techniques.
[src:databases/b-tree] One possibility is to use delta encoding to compress keys stored into each block.
[src:databases/b-tree] For internal blocks, space saving can be achieved by either compressing keys or pointers.
[src:databases/b-tree] For string keys, space can be saved by using the following technique: Normally the *i*-th entry of an internal block contains the first key of block ⁠ $i+1$ ⁠.
[src:databases/b-tree] Instead of storing the full key, we could store the shortest prefix of the first key of block ⁠ $i+1$ ⁠ that is strictly greater (in lexicographic order) than last key of block *i*.
[src:databases/b-tree] There is also a simple way to compress pointers: if we suppose that some consecutive blocks ⁠ $i,i+1,...i+k$ ⁠ are stored contiguously, then it will suffice to store only a pointer to the first block and the count of consecutive blocks.
[src:databases/b-tree] All the above compression techniques have some drawbacks.
[src:databases/b-tree] First, a full block must be decompressed to extract a single element.
[src:databases/b-tree] One technique to overcome this problem is to divide each block into sub-blocks and compress them separately.
[src:databases/b-tree] In this case searching or inserting an element will only need to decompress or compress a sub-block instead of a full block.
[src:databases/b-tree] Another drawback of compression techniques is that the number of stored elements may vary considerably from a block to another depending on how well the elements are compressed inside each block.
[src:databases/b-tree] The ReiserFS, NSS, XFS, JFS, ReFS, and BFS filesystems all use this type of tree for metadata indexing; BFS also uses B+ trees for storing directories.
[src:databases/b-tree] NTFS uses B+ trees for directory and security-related metadata indexing.
[src:databases/b-tree] EXT4 uses extent trees (a modified B+ tree data structure) for file extent indexing.
[src:databases/b-tree] APFS uses B+ trees to store mappings from filesystem object IDs to their locations on disk, and to store filesystem records (including directories), though these trees' leaf nodes lack sibling pointers.
[src:databases/b-tree] Relational database management systems such as IBM Db2, Informix, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle 8, Sybase ASE, and SQLite support this type of tree for table indices, though each such system implements the basic B+ tree structure with variations and extensions.
[src:databases/b-tree] Many NoSQL database management systems such as CouchDB and Tokyo Cabinet also support this type of tree for data access and storage.
[src:databases/b-tree] Finding objects in a high-dimensional database that are comparable to a particular query object is one of the most often utilized and yet expensive procedures in such systems.
[src:databases/b-tree] In such situations, finding the closest neighbor using a B+ tree is productive.
[src:databases/b-tree] B+ tree is efficiently used to construct an indexed search method called iDistance. iDistance searches for k nearest neighbors (kNN) in high-dimension metric spaces.
[src:databases/b-tree] The data in those high-dimension spaces is divided based on space or partition strategies, and each partition has an index value that is close with the respect to the partition.
[src:databases/b-tree] From here, those points can be efficiently implemented using B+ tree, thus, the queries are mapped to single dimensions ranged search.
[src:databases/b-tree] In other words, the iDistance technique can be viewed as a way of accelerating the sequential scan.
[src:databases/b-tree] Instead of scanning records from the beginning to the end of the data file, the iDistance starts the scan from spots where the nearest neighbors can be obtained early with a very high probability.
[src:databases/b-tree] Nonvolatile random-access memory (NVRAM) has been using B+ tree structure as the main memory access technique for the Internet Of Things (IoT) system because of its non static power consumption and high solidity of cell memory.
[src:databases/b-tree] B+ can regulate the trafficking of data to memory efficiently.
[src:databases/b-tree] Moreover, with advanced strategies on frequencies of some highly used leaf or reference point, the B+ tree shows significant results in increasing the endurance of database systems.
[src:databases/database-index] A **database index** is a data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on a database table at the cost of additional writes and storage space to maintain the index data structure.
[src:databases/database-index] Indexes are used to quickly locate data without having to search every row in a database table every time said table is accessed.
[src:databases/database-index] Indexes can be created using one or more columns of a database table, providing the basis for both rapid random lookups and efficient access of ordered records.
[src:databases/database-index] An index is a copy of selected columns of data, from a table, that is designed to enable very efficient search.
[src:databases/database-index] An index normally includes a "key" or direct link to the original row of data from which it was copied, to allow the complete row to be retrieved efficiently.
[src:databases/database-index] Some databases extend the power of indexing by letting developers create indexes on column values that have been transformed by functions or expressions.
[src:databases/database-index] For example, an index could be created on `upper(last_name)`, which would only store the upper-case versions of the `last_name` field in the index.
[src:databases/database-index] Another option sometimes supported is the use of partial index, where index entries are created only for those records that satisfy some conditional expression.
[src:databases/database-index] A further aspect of flexibility is to permit indexing on user-defined functions, as well as expressions formed from an assortment of built-in functions.
[src:databases/database-index] Most database software includes indexing technology that enables sub-linear time lookup to improve performance, as linear search is inefficient for large databases.
[src:databases/database-index] Suppose a database contains N data items and one must be retrieved based on the value of one of the fields.
[src:databases/database-index] A simple implementation retrieves and examines each item according to the test.
[src:databases/database-index] If there is only one matching item, this can stop when it finds that single item, but if there are multiple matches, it must test everything.
[src:databases/database-index] This means that the number of operations in the average case is O(N) or linear time.
[src:databases/database-index] Since databases may contain many objects, and since lookup is a common operation, it is often desirable to improve performance.
[src:databases/database-index] An index is any data structure that improves the performance of lookup.
[src:databases/database-index] There are many different data structures used for this purpose.
[src:databases/database-index] There are complex design trade-offs involving lookup performance, index size, and index-update performance.
[src:databases/database-index] Many index designs exhibit logarithmic (O(log(N))) lookup performance and in some applications it is possible to achieve flat (O(1)) performance.
[src:databases/database-index] Indexes are used to police database constraints, such as UNIQUE, EXCLUSION, PRIMARY KEY and FOREIGN KEY.
[src:databases/database-index] An index may be declared as UNIQUE, which creates an implicit constraint on the underlying table.
[src:databases/database-index] Database systems usually implicitly create an index on a set of columns declared PRIMARY KEY, and some are capable of using an already-existing index to police this constraint.
[src:databases/database-index] Many database systems require that both referencing and referenced sets of columns in a FOREIGN KEY constraint are indexed, thus improving performance of inserts, updates and deletes to the tables participating in the constraint.
[src:databases/database-index] Some database systems support an EXCLUSION constraint that ensures that, for a newly inserted or updated record, a certain predicate holds for no other record.
[src:databases/database-index] This can be used to implement a UNIQUE constraint (with equality predicate) or more complex constraints, like ensuring that no overlapping time ranges or no intersecting geometry objects would be stored in the table.
[src:databases/database-index] An index supporting fast searching for records satisfying the predicate is required to police such a constraint.
[src:databases/database-index] The data is present in arbitrary order, but the **logical ordering** is specified by the index.
[src:databases/database-index] The data rows may be spread throughout the table regardless of the value of the indexed column or expression.
[src:databases/database-index] The non-clustered index tree contains the index keys in sorted order, with the leaf level of the index containing the pointer to the record (page and the row number in the data page in page-organized engines; row offset in file-organized engines).
[src:databases/database-index] There can be more than one non-clustered index on a database table.
[src:databases/database-index] Clustering alters the data block into a certain distinct order to match the index, resulting in the row data being stored in order.
[src:databases/database-index] Therefore, only one clustered index can be created on a given database table.
[src:databases/database-index] Clustered indexes can greatly increase overall speed of retrieval, but usually only where the data is accessed sequentially in the same or reverse order of the clustered index, or when a range of items is selected.
[src:databases/database-index] Since the physical records are in this sort order on disk, the next row item in the sequence is immediately before or after the last one, and so fewer data block reads are required.
[src:databases/database-index] The primary feature of a clustered index is therefore the ordering of the physical data rows in accordance with the index blocks that point to them.
[src:databases/database-index] Some databases separate the data and index blocks into separate files, others put two completely different data blocks within the same physical file(s).
[src:databases/database-index] When multiple databases and multiple tables are joined, it is called a **cluster** (not to be confused with clustered index described previously).
[src:databases/database-index] The records for the tables sharing the value of a cluster key shall be stored together in the same or nearby data blocks.
[src:databases/database-index] This may improve the joins of these tables on the cluster key, since the matching records are stored together and less I/O is required to locate them.
[src:databases/database-index] The cluster configuration defines the data layout in the tables that are parts of the cluster.
[src:databases/database-index] A cluster can be keyed with a B-tree index or a hash table.
[src:databases/database-index] The data block where the table record is stored is defined by the value of the cluster key.
[src:databases/database-index] The order that the index definition defines the columns in is important.
[src:databases/database-index] It is possible to retrieve a set of row identifiers using only the first indexed column.
[src:databases/database-index] However, it is not possible or efficient (on most databases) to retrieve the set of row identifiers using only the second or greater indexed column.
[src:databases/database-index] For example, in a phone book organized by city first, then by last name, and then by first name, in a particular city, one can easily extract the list of all phone numbers.
[src:databases/database-index] However, it would be very tedious to find all the phone numbers for a particular last name.
[src:databases/database-index] One would have to look within each city's section for the entries with that last name.
[src:databases/database-index] Some databases can do this, others just won't use the index.
[src:databases/database-index] Then a sequential lookup checks the matching with `first_name`.
[src:databases/database-index] So, to improve the performance, one must ensure that the index is created on the order of search columns.
[src:databases/database-index] Indexes are useful for many applications but come with some limitations.
[src:databases/database-index] Consider the following SQL statement: `SELECT first_name FROM people WHERE last_name = 'Smith';`.
[src:databases/database-index] To process this statement without an index the database software must look at the last_name column on every row in the table (this is known as a full table scan).
[src:databases/database-index] With an index the database simply follows the index data structure (typically a B-tree) until the Smith entry has been found; this is much less computationally expensive than a full table scan.
[src:databases/database-index] Consider this SQL statement: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE email_address LIKE '%@wikipedia.org';`.
[src:databases/database-index] This query would yield an email address for every customer whose email address ends with "@wikipedia.org", but even if the email_address column has been indexed the database must perform a full index scan.
[src:databases/database-index] This is because the index is built with the assumption that words go from left to right.
[src:databases/database-index] With a wildcard at the beginning of the search-term, the database software is unable to use the underlying index data structure (in other words, the WHERE-clause is *not sargable*).
[src:databases/database-index] This problem can be solved through the addition of another index created on `reverse(email_address)` and a SQL query like this: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE reverse(email_address) LIKE reverse('%@wikipedia.org');`.
[src:databases/database-index] This puts the wild-card at the right-most part of the query (now gro.aidepikiw@%), which the index on reverse(email_address) can satisfy.
[src:databases/database-index] When the wildcard characters are used on both sides of the search word as *%wikipedia.org%*, the index available on this field is not used.
[src:databases/database-index] Rather only a sequential search is performed, which takes ⁠ $O(N)$ ⁠ time.
[src:databases/database-index] To mitigate this, a full-text indexing approach can be used.
[src:databases/database-index] A bitmap index is a special kind of indexing that stores the bulk of its data as bit arrays (bitmaps) and answers most queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:databases/database-index] The most commonly used indexes, such as B+ trees, are most efficient if the values they index do not repeat or repeat a small number of times.
[src:databases/database-index] In contrast, the bitmap index is designed for cases where the values of a variable repeat very frequently.
[src:databases/database-index] For example, the sex field in a customer database usually contains at most three distinct values: male, female or unknown (not recorded).
[src:databases/database-index] For such variables, the bitmap index can have a significant performance advantage over the commonly used trees.
[src:databases/database-index] A dense index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every record in the data file.
[src:databases/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer to *a record* in the sorted data file.
[src:databases/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the dense index points *to the first record* with that key.
[src:databases/database-index] A sparse index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every block in the data file.
[src:databases/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer *to the block* in the sorted data file.
[src:databases/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the sparse index points *to the lowest search key* in each block.
[src:databases/database-index] A reverse-key index reverses the key value before entering it in the index.
[src:databases/database-index] Reversing the key value is particularly useful for indexing data such as sequence numbers, where new key values monotonically increase.
[src:databases/database-index] An inverted index maps a content word to the document containing it, thereby allowing full-text searches.
[src:databases/database-index] The primary index contains the key fields of the table and a pointer to the non-key fields of the table.
[src:databases/database-index] The primary index is created automatically when the table is created in the database.
[src:databases/database-index] It is used to index fields that are neither ordering fields nor key fields (there is no assurance that the file is organized on key field or primary key field).
[src:databases/database-index] One index entry for every tuple in the data file (dense index) contains the value of the indexed attribute and pointer to the block or record.
[src:databases/database-index] Another type of index used in database systems is linear hashing.
[src:databases/database-index] Indices can be implemented using a variety of data structures.
[src:databases/database-index] Popular indices include balanced trees, B+ trees and hashes.
[src:databases/database-index] In Microsoft SQL Server, the leaf node of the clustered index corresponds to the actual data, not simply a pointer to data that resides elsewhere, as is the case with a non-clustered index.
[src:databases/database-index] Each relation can have a single clustered index and many unclustered indices.
[src:databases/database-index] An index is typically being accessed concurrently by several transactions and processes, and thus needs concurrency control.
[src:databases/database-index] While in principle indexes can utilize the common database concurrency control methods, specialized concurrency control methods for indexes exist, which are applied in conjunction with the common methods for a substantial performance gain.
[src:databases/database-index] In most cases, an index is used to quickly locate the data records from which the required data is read.
[src:databases/database-index] In other words, the index is only used to locate data records in the table and not to return data.
[src:databases/database-index] A covering index is a special case where the index itself contains the required data fields and can answer the required data.
[src:databases/database-index] To find the Name for ID 13, an index on (ID) is useful, but the record must still be read to get the Name.
[src:databases/database-index] However, an index on (ID, Name) contains the required data field and eliminates the need to look up the record.
[src:databases/database-index] Covering indexes are each for a specific table.
[src:databases/database-index] Queries which JOIN/ access across multiple tables, may potentially consider covering indexes on more than one of these tables.
[src:databases/database-index] A covering index can dramatically speed up data retrieval but may itself be large due to the additional keys, which slow down data insertion and update.
[src:databases/database-index] To reduce such index size, some systems allow including non-key fields in the index.
[src:databases/database-index] Non-key fields are not themselves part of the index ordering but only included at the leaf level, allowing for a covering index with less overall index size.
[src:databases/database-index] This can be done in SQL with `CREATE INDEX my_index ON my_table (id) INCLUDE (name);`.
[src:databases/database-index] No standard defines how to create indexes, because the ISO SQL Standard does not cover physical aspects.
[src:databases/database-index] Indexes are one of the physical parts of database conception among others like storage (tablespace or filegroups).
[src:databases/database-index] RDBMS vendors all give a `CREATE INDEX` syntax with some specific options that depend on their software's capabilities.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Normalization entails organizing the columns (attributes) and tables (relations) of a database to ensure that their dependencies are properly enforced by database integrity constraints.
[src:databases/database-normalization] It is accomplished by applying some formal rules either by a process of *synthesis* (creating a new database design) or *decomposition* (improving an existing database design).
[src:databases/database-normalization] A basic objective of the first normal form defined by Codd in 1970 was to permit data to be queried and manipulated using a "universal data sub-language" grounded in first-order logic.
[src:databases/database-normalization] An example of such a language is SQL, though it is one that Codd regarded as seriously flawed.
[src:databases/database-normalization] There are circumstances in which certain facts cannot be recorded at all.
[src:databases/database-normalization] For example, each record in a "Faculty and Their Courses" relation might contain a Faculty ID, Faculty Name, Faculty Hire Date, and Course Code.
[src:databases/database-normalization] The same information can be expressed on multiple rows; therefore updates to the relation may result in logical inconsistencies.
[src:databases/database-normalization] For example, each record in an "Employees' Skills" relation might contain an Employee ID, Employee Address, and Skill; thus a change of address for a particular employee may need to be applied to multiple records (one for each skill).
[src:databases/database-normalization] If the update is only partially successful – the employee's address is updated on some records but not others – then the relation is left in an inconsistent state.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Specifically, the relation provides conflicting answers to the question of what this particular employee's address is.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Under certain circumstances, the deletion of data representing certain facts necessitates the deletion of data representing completely different facts.
[src:databases/database-normalization] A fully normalized database can be extended to accommodate new types of data with minimal changes to its existing structure.
[src:databases/database-normalization] As a result, applications interacting with the database are minimally affected.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Normalized relations and the relationships between them mirror real-world concepts and their interrelationships.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Codd introduced the concept of normalization and what is now known as the first normal form (1NF) in 1970.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Codd went on to define the second normal form (2NF) and third normal form (3NF) in 1971, and Codd and Raymond F.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Boyce defined the Boyce–Codd normal form (BCNF) in 1974.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Ronald Fagin introduced the fourth normal form (4NF) in 1977 and the fifth normal form (5NF) in 1979.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Date introduced the sixth normal form (6NF) in 2003.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Informally, a relational database relation is often described as "normalized" if it meets third normal form.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Most 3NF relations are free of insertion, updation, and deletion anomalies.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Normalization is a database design technique, which is used to design a relational database table up to higher normal form.
[src:databases/database-normalization] The process is progressive, and a higher level of database normalization cannot be achieved unless the previous levels have been satisfied.
[src:databases/database-normalization] However, normal forms beyond 4NF are mainly of academic interest, as the problems they exist to solve rarely appear in practice.
[src:databases/database-normalization] For this example it is assumed that each book has only one author.
[src:databases/database-normalization] A table that conforms to the relational model has a primary key which uniquely identifies a row.
[src:databases/database-normalization] In the first normal form each field contains a single value.
[src:databases/database-normalization] A field may not contain a set of values or a nested record.
[src:databases/database-normalization] **Subject** contains a set of subject values, meaning it does not comply.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Instead of one table in unnormalized form, there are now two tables conforming to the 1NF.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Recall that the **Book** table below has a composite key of **{Title, Format}**, which will not satisfy 2NF if some subset of that key is a determinant.
[src:databases/database-normalization] At this point in our design the **key** is not finalized as the primary key, so it is called a candidate key.
[src:databases/database-normalization] All of the attributes that are not part of the candidate key depend on *Title*, but only *Price* also depends on *Format*.
[src:databases/database-normalization] To conform to 2NF and remove duplicates, every non-candidate-key attribute must depend on the whole candidate key, not just part of it.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Now, both the **Book** and **Price** tables conform to 2NF.
[src:databases/database-normalization] The **Book** table still has a transitive functional dependency ({Author Nationality} is dependent on {Author}, which is dependent on {Title}).
[src:databases/database-normalization] Similar violations exist for publisher ({Publisher Country} is dependent on {Publisher}, which is dependent on {Title}) and for genre ({Genre Name} is dependent on {Genre ID}, which is dependent on {Title}).
[src:databases/database-normalization] Hence, the **Book** table is not in 3NF.
[src:databases/database-normalization] The elementary key normal form (EKNF) falls strictly between 3NF and BCNF and is not much discussed in the literature.
[src:databases/database-normalization] It is intended *"to capture the salient qualities of both 3NF and BCNF"* while avoiding the problems of both (namely, that 3NF is "too forgiving" and BCNF is "prone to computational complexity").
[src:databases/database-normalization] Since it is rarely mentioned in literature, it is not included in this example.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Assume the database is owned by a book retailer franchise that has several franchisees that own shops in different locations.
[src:databases/database-normalization] As this table structure consists of a compound primary key, it does not contain any non-key attributes and it is already in BCNF (and therefore also satisfies all the previous normal forms).
[src:databases/database-normalization] However, assuming that all available books are offered in each area, the **Title** is not unambiguously bound to a certain **Location** and therefore the table does not satisfy 4NF.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Now, every record is unambiguously identified by a superkey, therefore 4NF is satisfied.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Suppose the franchisees can also order books from different suppliers.
[src:databases/database-normalization] The decomposition produces ETNF compliance.
[src:databases/database-normalization] To spot a table not satisfying the 5NF, it is usually necessary to examine the data thoroughly.
[src:databases/database-normalization] It actually is not possible to join these three tables.
[src:databases/database-normalization] That means it was not possible to decompose the **Franchisee – Book – Location** without data loss, therefore the table already satisfies 5NF.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Date has argued that only a database in 5NF is truly "normalized".
[src:databases/database-normalization] Logically, **Thickness** is determined by number of pages.
[src:databases/database-normalization] That means it depends on **Pages** which is not a key.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Let's set an example convention saying a book up to 350 pages is considered "slim" and a book over 350 pages is considered "thick".
[src:databases/database-normalization] This convention is technically a constraint but it is neither a domain constraint nor a key constraint; therefore we cannot rely on domain constraints and key constraints to keep the data integrity.
[src:databases/database-normalization] In other words – nothing prevents us from putting, for example, "Thick" for a book with only 50 pages – and this makes the table violate DKNF.
[src:databases/database-normalization] That way, the domain integrity violation has been eliminated, and the table is in DKNF.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Normalization does not prevent all cases of impossible/conflicting/unpredictable output.
[src:databases/database-normalization] It would therefore be better to specify and use only Min pages.
[src:databases/database-normalization] The obvious drawback of 6NF is the proliferation of tables required to represent the information on a single entity.
[src:databases/database-normalization] If a table in 5NF has one primary key column and N attributes, representing the same information in 6NF will require N tables; multi-field updates to a single conceptual record will require updates to multiple tables; and inserts and deletes will similarly require operations across multiple tables.
[src:databases/database-normalization] For this reason, in databases intended to serve online transaction processing (OLTP) needs, 6NF should not be used.
[src:databases/database-normalization] However, in data warehouses, which do not permit interactive updates and which are specialized for fast query on large data volumes, certain DBMSs use an internal 6NF representation – known as a columnar data store.
[src:databases/database-normalization] In situations where the number of unique values of a column is far less than the number of rows in the table, column-oriented storage allow significant savings in space through data compression.
[src:databases/database-normalization] In all these cases, however, the database designer does not have to perform 6NF normalization manually by creating separate tables.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Some DBMSs that are specialized for warehousing, such as Sybase IQ, use columnar storage by default, but the designer still sees only a single multi-column table.
[src:databases/database-normalization] Other DBMSs, such as Microsoft SQL Server 2012 and later, let you specify a "columnstore index" for a particular table.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A **database transaction** symbolizes a unit of work, performed within a database management system (or similar system) against a database, that is treated in a coherent and reliable way independent of other transactions.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A transaction generally represents any change in a database.
[src:databases/database-transaction] To provide isolation between programs accessing a database concurrently.
[src:databases/database-transaction] If this isolation is not provided, the programs' outcomes are possibly erroneous.
[src:databases/database-transaction] In a database management system, a transaction is a single unit of logic or work, sometimes made up of multiple operations.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Any logical calculation done in a consistent mode in a database is known as a transaction.
[src:databases/database-transaction] One example is a transfer from one bank account to another: the complete transaction requires subtracting the amount to be transferred from one account and adding that same amount to the other.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Database practitioners often refer to these properties of database transactions using the acronym ACID.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Databases and other data stores which treat the integrity of data as paramount often include the ability to handle transactions to maintain the integrity of data.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A single transaction consists of one or more independent units of work, each reading and/or writing information to a database or other data store.
[src:databases/database-transaction] When this happens it is often important to ensure that all such processing leaves the database or data store in a consistent state.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Examples from double-entry accounting systems often illustrate the concept of transactions.
[src:databases/database-transaction] In double-entry accounting every debit requires the recording of an associated credit.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A transactional system would make both entries pass or both entries would fail.
[src:databases/database-transaction] By treating the recording of multiple entries as an atomic transactional unit of work the system maintains the integrity of the data recorded.
[src:databases/database-transaction] In other words, nobody ends up with a situation in which a debit is recorded but no associated credit is recorded, or vice versa.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A **transactional database** is a DBMS that provides the ACID properties for a bracketed set of database operations (begin-commit).
[src:databases/database-transaction] Transactions ensure that the database is always in a consistent state, even in the event of concurrent updates and failures.
[src:databases/database-transaction] All the write operations within a transaction have an all-or-nothing effect, that is, either the transaction succeeds and all writes take effect, or otherwise, the database is brought to a state that does not include any of the writes of the transaction.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Transactions also ensure that the effect of concurrent transactions satisfies certain guarantees, known as isolation level.
[src:databases/database-transaction] The highest isolation level is serializability, which guarantees that the effect of concurrent transactions is equivalent to their serial (i.e. sequential) execution.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Most modern relational database management systems support transactions.
[src:databases/database-transaction] NoSQL databases prioritize scalability along with supporting transactions in order to guarantee data consistency in the event of concurrent updates and accesses.
[src:databases/database-transaction] In a database system, a transaction might consist of one or more data-manipulation statements and queries, each reading and/or writing information in the database.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Users of database systems consider consistency and integrity of data as highly important.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Execute a set of data manipulations and/or queries.
[src:databases/database-transaction] If no error occurs, then commit the transaction.
[src:databases/database-transaction] If an error occurs, then roll back the transaction.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A transaction commit operation persists all the results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A transaction rollback operation does not persist the partial results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:databases/database-transaction] In no case can a partial transaction be committed to the database since that would leave the database in an inconsistent state.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Internally, multi-user databases store and process transactions, often by using a transaction ID or XID.
[src:databases/database-transaction] There are multiple varying ways for transactions to be implemented other than the simple way documented above.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Nested transactions, for example, are transactions which contain statements within them that start new transactions (i.e. sub-transactions).
[src:databases/database-transaction] *Multi-level transactions* are a variant of nested transactions where the sub-transactions take place at different levels of a layered system architecture (e.g., with one operation at the database-engine level, one operation at the operating-system level).
[src:databases/database-transaction] Another type of transaction is the compensating transaction.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Transactions are available in most SQL database implementations, though with varying levels of robustness.
[src:databases/database-transaction] For example, MySQL began supporting transactions from early version 3.23, but the InnoDB storage engine was not default before version 5.5.
[src:databases/database-transaction] The earlier available storage engine, MyISAM does not support transactions.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A transaction is typically started using the command `BEGIN` (although the SQL standard specifies `START TRANSACTION`).
[src:databases/database-transaction] When the system processes a `COMMIT` statement, the transaction ends with successful completion.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A `ROLLBACK` statement can also end the transaction, undoing any work performed since `BEGIN`.
[src:databases/database-transaction] If autocommit was disabled with the start of a transaction, autocommit will also be re-enabled with the end of the transaction.
[src:databases/database-transaction] One can set the isolation level for individual transactional operations as well as globally.
[src:databases/database-transaction] At the highest level (`READ COMMITTED`), the result of any operation performed after a transaction has started will remain invisible to other database users until the transaction has ended.
[src:databases/database-transaction] At the lowest level (`READ UNCOMMITTED`), which may occasionally be used to ensure high concurrency, such changes will be immediately visible.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Relational databases are traditionally composed of tables with fixed-size fields and records.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Object databases comprise variable-sized blobs, possibly serializable or incorporating a mime-type.
[src:databases/database-transaction] The fundamental similarities between Relational and Object databases are the start and the commit or rollback.
[src:databases/database-transaction] After starting a transaction, database records or objects are locked, either read-only or read-write.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Once the transaction is fully defined, changes are committed or rolled back atomically, such that at the end of the transaction there is no inconsistency.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Database systems implement distributed transactions as transactions accessing data over multiple nodes.
[src:databases/database-transaction] A distributed transaction enforces the ACID properties over multiple nodes, and might include systems such as databases, storage managers, file systems, messaging systems, and other data managers.
[src:databases/database-transaction] In a distributed transaction there is typically an entity coordinating all the process to ensure that all parts of the transaction are applied to all relevant systems.
[src:databases/database-transaction] Moreover, the integration of Storage as a Service (StaaS) within these environments is crucial, as it offers a virtually infinite pool of storage resources, accommodating a range of cloud-based data store classes with varying availability, scalability, and ACID properties.
[src:databases/database-transaction] This integration is essential for achieving higher availability, lower response time, and cost efficiency in data-intensive applications deployed across cloud-based data stores.
[src:databases/database-transaction] The Namesys Reiser4 filesystem for Linux supports transactions, and as of Microsoft Windows Vista, the Microsoft NTFS filesystem supports distributed transactions across networks.
[src:databases/database-transaction] There is occurring research into more data coherent filesystems, such as the Warp Transactional Filesystem (WTF).
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In database systems, **isolation** is one of the ACID (*Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability*) transaction properties.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] It determines how transaction integrity is visible to other users and systems.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A lower isolation level increases the ability of many users to access the same data at the same time, but also increases the number of concurrency effects (such as dirty reads or lost updates) users might encounter.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Conversely, a higher isolation level reduces the types of concurrency effects that users may encounter, but requires more system resources and increases the chances that one transaction will block another.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Concurrency control comprises the underlying mechanisms in a DBMS which handle isolation and guarantee related correctness.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] It is heavily used by the database and storage engines both to guarantee the correct execution of concurrent transactions, and (via different mechanisms) the correctness of other DBMS processes.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] The transaction-related mechanisms typically constrain the database data access operations' timing (transaction schedules) to certain orders characterized as the serializability and recoverability schedule properties.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Constraining database access operation execution typically means reduced performance (measured by rates of execution), and thus concurrency control mechanisms are typically designed to provide the best performance possible under the constraints.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Often, when possible without harming correctness, the serializability property is compromised for better performance.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] However, recoverability cannot be compromised, since such typically results in a database integrity violation.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Two-phase locking is the most common transaction concurrency control method in DBMSs, used to provide both serializability and recoverability for correctness.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In order to access a database object a transaction first needs to acquire a lock for this object.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Depending on the access operation type (e.g., reading or writing an object) and on the lock type, acquiring the lock may be blocked and postponed, if another transaction is holding a lock for that object.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Isolation is typically enforced at the database level.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] However, various client-side systems can also be used.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] It can be controlled in application frameworks or runtime containers such as J2EE Entity Beans On older systems, it may be implemented systemically (by the application developers), for example through the use of temporary tables.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In two-tier, three-tier, or n-tier web applications a transaction manager can be used to maintain isolation.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A transaction manager is middleware which sits between an app service (back-end application service) and the operating system.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A transaction manager can provide global isolation and atomicity.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] It tracks when new servers join a transaction and coordinates an atomic commit protocol among the servers.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] The details are abstracted from the app, making transactions simpler and easier to code.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A transaction processing monitor (TPM) is a collection of middle-ware including a transaction manager.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A TPM might provide local isolation to an app with a lock manager.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] The ANSI/ISO standard SQL 92 refers to three different *read phenomena* when a transaction retrieves data that another transaction might have updated.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In the following examples, two transactions take place.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In transaction 1, a query is performed, then in transaction 2, an update is performed, and finally in transaction 1, the same query is performed again.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A *dirty read* (aka *uncommitted dependency*) occurs when a transaction retrieves a row that has been updated by another transaction that is not yet committed.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In this example, transaction 1 retrieves the row with id 1, then transaction 2 updates the row with id 1, and finally transaction 1 retrieves the row with id 1 again.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Now if transaction 2 rolls back its update (already retrieved by transaction 1) or performs other updates, then the view of the row may be wrong in transaction 1.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] At the READ UNCOMMITTED isolation level, the second SELECT in transaction 1 retrieves the updated row: this is a dirty read.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] At the READ COMMITTED, REPEATABLE READ, and SERIALIZABLE isolation levels, the second SELECT in transaction 1 retrieves the initial row.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A *non-repeatable read* occurs when a transaction retrieves a row twice and that row is updated by another transaction that is committed in between.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In this example, transaction 1 retrieves the row with id 1, then transaction 2 updates the row with id 1 and is committed, and finally transaction 1 retrieves the row with id 1 again.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] At the READ UNCOMMITTED and READ COMMITTED isolation levels, the second SELECT in transaction 1 retrieves the updated row: this is a non-repeatable read.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] At the REPEATABLE READ and SERIALIZABLE isolation levels, the second SELECT in transaction 1 retrieves the initial row.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A *phantom read* occurs when a transaction retrieves a set of rows twice and new rows are inserted into or removed from that set by another transaction that is committed in between.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In this example, transaction 1 retrieves the set of rows with age greater than 17, then transaction 2 inserts a row with age 26 and is committed, and finally transaction 1 retrieves the set of rows with age greater than 17 again.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] At the READ UNCOMMITTED, READ COMMITTED, and REPEATABLE READ isolation levels, the second SELECT in transaction 1 retrieves the new set of rows that includes the inserted row: this is a phantom read.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] At the SERIALIZABLE isolation level, the second SELECT in transaction 1 retrieves the initial set of rows.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] There are two basic strategies used to prevent non-repeatable reads and phantom reads.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In the first strategy, *lock-based concurrency control*, transaction 2 is committed after transaction 1 is committed or rolled back.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] It produces the serial schedule *T1, T2*.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Under lock-based concurrency control, non-repeatable reads and phantom reads may occur when read locks are not acquired when performing a SELECT, or when the acquired locks on affected rows are released as soon as the SELECT is performed.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Under multiversion concurrency control, non-repeatable reads and phantom reads may occur when the requirement that a transaction affected by a commit conflict must be rolled back is relaxed.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Of the four ACID properties in a DBMS (Database Management System), the isolation property is the one most often relaxed.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] When attempting to maintain the highest level of isolation, a DBMS usually acquires locks on data which may result in a loss of concurrency, or implements multiversion concurrency control.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] This requires adding logic for the application to function correctly.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Most DBMSs offer a number of *transaction isolation levels*, which control the degree of locking that occurs when selecting data.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] For many database applications, the majority of database transactions can be constructed to avoid requiring high isolation levels (e.g.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] SERIALIZABLE level), thus reducing the locking overhead for the system.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] The programmer must carefully analyze database access code to ensure that any relaxation of isolation does not cause software bugs that are difficult to find.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Conversely, if higher isolation levels are used, the possibility of deadlock is increased, which also requires careful analysis and programming techniques to avoid.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] The isolation levels defined by the ANSI/ISO SQL standard are listed as follows.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] With a lock-based concurrency control DBMS implementation, serializability requires read and write locks (acquired on selected data) to be released at the end of the transaction.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Also *range-locks* must be acquired when a SELECT query uses a ranged *WHERE* clause, especially to avoid the ***phantom reads*** phenomenon.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] When using non-lock based concurrency control, no locks are acquired; however, if the system detects a *write collision* among several concurrent transactions, only one of them is allowed to commit.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] See *snapshot isolation* for more details on this topic.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] From : (Second Informal Review Draft) ISO/IEC 9075:1992, Database Language SQL- July 30, 1992: *The execution of concurrent SQL-transactions at isolation level SERIALIZABLE is guaranteed to be serializable.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] A serializable execution is defined to be an execution of the operations of concurrently executing SQL-transactions that produces the same effect as some serial execution of those same SQL-transactions.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In this isolation level, a lock-based concurrency control DBMS implementation keeps read and write locks (acquired on selected data) until the end of the transaction.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] However, *range-locks* are not managed, so ***phantom reads*** can occur.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Write skew is possible at this isolation level in some systems.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Write skew is a phenomenon where two writes are allowed to the same column(s) in a table by two different writers (who have previously read the columns they are updating), resulting in the column having data that is a mix of the two transactions.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] As in the previous level, *range-locks* are not managed.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Putting it in simpler words, read committed is an isolation level that guarantees that any data read is committed at the moment it is read.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] It simply restricts the reader from seeing any intermediate, uncommitted, 'dirty' read.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] It makes no promise whatsoever that if the transaction re-issues the read, it will find the same data; data is free to change after it is read.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In this level, ***dirty reads*** are allowed, so one transaction may see *not-yet-committed* changes made by other transactions.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] The *default isolation level* of different DBMS's varies quite widely.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Most databases that feature transactions allow the user to set any isolation level.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Some DBMS's also require additional syntax when performing a SELECT statement to acquire locks (e.g.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] FOR UPDATE* to acquire exclusive write locks on accessed rows).
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] This paper shows a number of weaknesses in the anomaly approach to defining isolation levels.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] The three ANSI phenomena are ambiguous, and even in their loosest interpretations do not exclude some anomalous behavior ...
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] This leads to some counter-intuitive results.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] In particular, lock-based isolation levels have different characteristics than their ANSI equivalents.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] This is disconcerting because commercial database systems typically use locking implementations.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Additionally, the ANSI phenomena do not distinguish between a number of types of isolation level behavior that are popular in commercial systems.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] ... it relies in subtle ways on an assumption that a locking schema is used for concurrency control, as opposed to an optimistic or multi-version concurrency scheme.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] Anomaly serializable is not the same as serializable.
[src:databases/isolation-database-systems] That is, it is necessary, but not sufficient that a serializable schedule should be free of all three phenomena types.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Without concurrency control, if someone is reading from a database at the same time as someone else is writing to it, it is possible that the reader will see a half-written or inconsistent piece of data.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] For instance, when making a wire transfer between two bank accounts if a reader reads the balance at the bank when the money has been withdrawn from the original account and before it was deposited in the destination account, it would seem that money has disappeared from the bank.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Isolation is the property that provides guarantees in the concurrent accesses to data.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Isolation is implemented by means of a concurrency control protocol.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The simplest way is to make all readers wait until the writer is done, which is known as a read-write lock.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Locks are known to create contention especially between long read transactions and update transactions.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC aims at solving the problem by keeping multiple copies of each data item.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] In this way, each user connected to the database sees a *snapshot* of the database at a particular instant in time.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] When an MVCC database needs to update a piece of data, it will not overwrite the original data item with new data, but instead creates a newer version of the data item.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Thus there are multiple versions stored.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The version that each transaction sees depends on the isolation level implemented.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The most common isolation level implemented with MVCC is snapshot isolation.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] With snapshot isolation, a transaction observes a state of the data as of when the transaction started.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC provides point-in-time consistent views.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Read transactions under MVCC typically use a timestamp or transaction ID to determine what state of the DB to read, and read these versions of the data.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Read and write transactions are thus isolated from each other without any need for locking.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] However, despite locks being unnecessary, they are used by some MVCC databases such as Oracle.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Writes create a newer version, while concurrent reads access an older version.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC introduces the challenge of how to remove versions that become obsolete and will never be read.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] In some cases, a process to periodically sweep through and delete the obsolete versions is implemented.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] This is often a stop-the-world process that traverses a whole table and rewrites it with the last version of each data item.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] PostgreSQL can use this approach with its VACUUM FREEZE process.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Other databases split the storage blocks into two parts: the data part and an undo log.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The data part always keeps the last committed version.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The undo log enables the recreation of older versions of data.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The main inherent limitation of this latter approach is that when there are update-intensive workloads, the undo log part runs out of space and then transactions are aborted as they cannot be given their snapshot.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] For a document-oriented database it also allows the system to optimize documents by writing entire documents onto contiguous sections of disk—when updated, the entire document can be re-written rather than bits and pieces cut out or maintained in a linked, non-contiguous database structure.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC uses timestamps (**TS**), and *incrementing transaction IDs*, to achieve *transactional consistency*.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC ensures a transaction (**T**) never has to wait to *Read* a database object (**P**) by maintaining several versions of the object.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Each version of object **P** has both a *Read Timestamp* (**RTS**) and a *Write Timestamp* (**WTS**) which lets a particular transaction **Ti** read the most recent version of the object which precedes the transaction's *Read Timestamp* **RTS**(**Ti**).
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] A *Write* cannot complete if there are other outstanding transactions with an earlier Read Timestamp (**RTS**) to the same object.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Like people standing in line at a store, they cannot complete their checkout transaction until those in front complete theirs.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] (This is because a later transaction already depends on the old value.) Otherwise, **Ti** creates a new version of object **P** and sets the read/write timestamp **TS** of the new version to the timestamp of the transaction **TS** ← **TS**(**Ti**).
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The drawback to this system is the cost of storing multiple versions of objects in the database.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] On the other hand, reads are never blocked, which can be important for workloads mostly involving reading values from the database.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] MVCC is particularly adept at implementing true snapshot isolation, something which other methods of concurrency control frequently do either incompletely or with high performance costs.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] A structure to hold a record (row) for a database using MVCC could look like this in Rust.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The MVCC transaction identifier for insert.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The MVCC transaction identifier for delete.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] T0 wrote Object 1="Foo" and Object 2="Bar".
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] After that T1 wrote Object 1="Hello" leaving Object 2 at its original value.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The new value of Object 1 will supersede the value at 0 for all transactions that start after T1 commits at which point version 0 of Object 1 can be garbage collected.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] There is a new version as of time 2 of Object 2 which is marked as deleted and a new Object 3.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Since T2 and T3 run concurrently T2 sees the version of the database before 2 i.e. before T3 committed writes, as such T2 reads Object 2="Bar" and Object 1="Hello".
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] This is how multiversion concurrency control allows snapshot isolation reads without any locks.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Multiversion concurrency control is described in some detail in the 1981 paper "Concurrency Control in Distributed Database Systems" by Phil Bernstein and Nathan Goodman, then employed by the Computer Corporation of America.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Bernstein and Goodman's paper cites a 1978 dissertation by David P.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Reed which quite clearly describes MVCC and claims it as an original work.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] The first shipping, commercial database software product featuring MVCC was VAX Rdb/ELN, released in 1984, and created at Digital Equipment Corporation by Jim Starkey.
[src:databases/multiversion-concurrency-control] Starkey went on to create the second commercially successful MVCC database - InterBase.
[src:databases/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:databases/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:databases/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:databases/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:databases/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:databases/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:databases/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:databases/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:databases/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:databases/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:databases/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:databases/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:databases/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:databases/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:databases/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:databases/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:databases/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:databases/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:databases/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:databases/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:databases/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:databases/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:databases/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:databases/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:databases/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:databases/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:databases/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:databases/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:databases/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:databases/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:databases/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:databases/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:databases/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:databases/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:databases/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:databases/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:databases/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:databases/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:databases/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:databases/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:databases/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:databases/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:databases/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:databases/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:databases/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:databases/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:databases/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:databases/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:databases/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:databases/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:databases/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:databases/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:databases/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:databases/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:databases/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:databases/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Generally, the query optimizer cannot be accessed directly by users: once queries are submitted to the database server, and parsed by the parser, they are then passed to the query optimizer where optimization occurs.
[src:databases/query-optimization] However, some database engines allow guiding the query optimizer with hints.
[src:databases/query-optimization] A query is a request for information from a database.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Since database structures are complex, in most cases, and especially for not-very-simple queries, the needed data for a query can be collected from a database by accessing it in different ways, through different data-structures, and in different orders.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Each different way typically requires different processing time.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Processing times of the same query may have large variance, from a fraction of a second to hours, depending on the chosen method.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The purpose of query optimization, which is an automated process, is to find the way to process a given query in minimum time.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The large possible variance in time justifies performing query optimization, though finding the exact optimal query plan, among all possibilities, is typically very complex, time-consuming by itself, may be too costly, and often practically impossible.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Thus query optimization typically tries to approximate the optimum by comparing several common-sense alternatives to provide in a reasonable time a "good enough" plan which typically does not deviate much from the best possible result.
[src:databases/query-optimization] There is a trade-off between the amount of time spent figuring out the best query plan and the quality of the choice; the optimizer may not choose the best answer on its own.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Different qualities of database management systems have different ways of balancing these two.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Cost-based query optimizers evaluate the resource footprint of various query plans and use this as the basis for plan selection.
[src:databases/query-optimization] These assign an estimated "cost" to each possible query plan, and choose the plan with the smallest cost.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Costs are used to estimate the runtime cost of evaluating the query, in terms of the number of I/O operations required, CPU path length, amount of disk buffer space, disk storage service time, and interconnect usage between units of parallelism, and other factors determined from the data dictionary.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The set of query plans examined is formed by examining the possible access paths (e.g., primary index access, secondary index access, full file scan) and various relational table join techniques (e.g., merge join, hash join, product join).
[src:databases/query-optimization] The search space can become quite large depending on the complexity of the SQL query.
[src:databases/query-optimization] These consist of logical optimization—which generates a sequence of relational algebra to solve the query—and physical optimization—which is used to determine the means of carrying out each operation.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Most query optimizers represent query plans as a tree of "plan nodes".
[src:databases/query-optimization] A plan node encapsulates a single operation that is required to execute the query.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The nodes are arranged as a tree, in which intermediate results flow from the bottom of the tree to the top.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Each node has zero or more child nodes—those are nodes whose output is fed as input to the parent node.
[src:databases/query-optimization] For example, a join node will have two child nodes, which represent the two join operands, whereas a sort node would have a single child node (the input to be sorted).
[src:databases/query-optimization] The leaves of the tree are nodes which produce results by scanning the disk, for example by performing an index scan or a sequential scan.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The performance of a query plan is determined largely by the order in which the tables are joined.
[src:databases/query-optimization] For example, when joining 3 tables A, B, C of size 10 rows, 10,000 rows, and 1,000,000 rows, respectively, a query plan that joins B and C first can take several orders-of-magnitude more time to execute than one that joins A and C first.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Most query optimizers determine join order via a dynamic programming algorithm pioneered by IBM's System R database project .
[src:databases/query-optimization] The optimizer then considers combining each pair of relations for which a join condition exists.
[src:databases/query-optimization] For each pair, the optimizer will consider the available join algorithms implemented by the DBMS.
[src:databases/query-optimization] It will preserve the cheapest way to join each pair of relations, in addition to the cheapest way to join each pair of relations that produces its output according to a particular sort order.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Then all three-relation query plans are computed, by joining each two-relation plan produced by the previous phase with the remaining relations in the query.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Sort order can avoid a redundant sort operation later on in processing the query.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Second, a particular sort order can speed up a subsequent join because it clusters the data in a particular way.
[src:databases/query-optimization] A SQL query to a modern relational DBMS does more than just selections and joins.
[src:databases/query-optimization] In particular, SQL queries often nest several layers of SPJ blocks (Select-Project-Join), by means of group by, exists, and not exists operators.
[src:databases/query-optimization] In some cases such nested SQL queries can be flattened into a select-project-join query, but not always.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Query plans for nested SQL queries can also be chosen using the same dynamic programming algorithm as used for join ordering, but this can lead to an enormous escalation in query optimization time.
[src:databases/query-optimization] So some database management systems use an alternative rule-based approach that uses a query graph model.
[src:databases/query-optimization] One of the hardest problems in query optimization is to accurately estimate the costs of alternative query plans.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Optimizers cost query plans using a mathematical model of query execution costs that relies heavily on estimates of the cardinality, or number of tuples, flowing through each edge in a query plan.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Cardinality estimation in turn depends on estimates of the selection factor of predicates in the query.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Traditionally, database systems estimate selectivities through fairly detailed statistics on the distribution of values in each column, such as histograms.
[src:databases/query-optimization] This technique works well for estimation of selectivities of individual predicates.
[src:databases/query-optimization] However many queries have conjunctions of predicates such as `select count(*) from R where R.make='Honda' and R.model='Accord'`.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Query predicates are often highly correlated (for example, `model='Accord'` implies `make='Honda'`), and it is very hard to estimate the selectivity of the conjunct in general.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Poor cardinality estimates and uncaught correlation are one of the main reasons why query optimizers pick poor query plans.
[src:databases/query-optimization] This is one reason why a database administrator should regularly update the database statistics, especially after major data loads/unloads.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Classical query optimization assumes that query plans are compared according to one single cost metric, usually execution time, and that the cost of each query plan can be calculated without uncertainty.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Both assumptions are sometimes violated in practice and multiple extensions of classical query optimization have been studied in the research literature that overcome those limitations.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Those extended problem variants differ in how they model the cost of single query plans and in terms of their optimization goal.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Classical query optimization associates each query plan with one scalar cost value.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization assumes that query plan cost depends on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Such parameters can for instance represent the selectivity of query predicates that are not fully specified at optimization time but will be provided at execution time.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization therefore associates each query plan with a cost function that maps from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a one-dimensional cost space.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is usually to generate all query plans that could be optimal for any of the possible parameter value combinations.
[src:databases/query-optimization] This yields a set of relevant query plans.
[src:databases/query-optimization] At run time, the best plan is selected out of that set once the true parameter values become known.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The advantage of parametric query optimization is that optimization (which is in general a very expensive operation) is avoided at run time.
[src:databases/query-optimization] There are often other cost metrics in addition to execution time that are relevant to compare query plans.
[src:databases/query-optimization] In a cloud computing scenario for instance, one should compare query plans not only in terms of how much time they take to execute but also in terms of how much money their execution costs.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Or in the context of approximate query optimization, it is possible to execute query plans on randomly selected samples of the input data in order to obtain approximate results with reduced execution overhead.
[src:databases/query-optimization] In such cases, alternative query plans must be compared in terms of their execution time but also in terms of the precision or reliability of the data they generate.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Multi-objective query optimization models the cost of a query plan as a cost vector where each vector component represents cost according to a different cost metric.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Classical query optimization can be considered as a special case of multi-objective query optimization where the dimension of the cost space (i.e., the number of cost vector components) is one.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Different cost metrics might conflict with each other (e.g., there might be one plan with minimal execution time and a different plan with minimal monetary execution fees in a cloud computing scenario).
[src:databases/query-optimization] Therefore, the goal of optimization cannot be to find a query plan that minimizes all cost metrics but must be to find a query plan that realizes the best compromise between different cost metrics.
[src:databases/query-optimization] What the best compromise is depends on user preferences (e.g., some users might prefer a cheaper plan while others prefer a faster plan in a cloud scenario).
[src:databases/query-optimization] Multi-objective parametric query optimization generalizes parametric and multi-objective query optimization.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Plans are compared according to multiple cost metrics and plan costs may depend on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The cost of a query plan is therefore modeled as a function from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a multi-dimensional cost space.
[src:databases/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is to generate the set of query plans that can be optimal for each possible combination of parameter values and user preferences.
[src:databases/query-optimization] A number of tools display query execution plans to show which operations have the highest processing cost.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Microsoft SMS, ApexSQLPlan, Hana, and Tableau are some examples.
[src:databases/query-optimization] Fixing these issues found in these plans can shave tens of percent execution time, and in some cases can cut two-dimensional searches to linear ones.
[src:databases/query-optimization] One of the primary and simplest optimization checklists is to use operations that most RDMS are designed to execute efficiently.
[src:databases/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:databases/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:databases/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:databases/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:databases/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:databases/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:databases/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:databases/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:databases/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:databases/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:databases/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:databases/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:databases/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:databases/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:databases/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:databases/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:databases/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:databases/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:databases/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:databases/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:databases/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:databases/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:databases/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:databases/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:databases/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:databases/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:databases/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:databases/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:databases/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:databases/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:databases/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:databases/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:databases/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:databases/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:databases/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:databases/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:databases/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:databases/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:databases/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:databases/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:databases/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:databases/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:databases/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:databases/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:databases/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:databases/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:databases/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:databases/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:databases/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:databases/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:databases/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:databases/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:databases/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:databases/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:databases/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:databases/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:databases/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:databases/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:databases/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:databases/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:databases/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:databases/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:databases/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:databases/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:databases/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:databases/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:databases/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:databases/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:databases/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:databases/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:databases/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:databases/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:databases/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:databases/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:databases/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:databases/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:databases/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:databases/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:databases/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:databases/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:databases/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:databases/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:databases/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:databases/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:databases/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:databases/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:databases/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:databases/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:databases/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:databases/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:databases/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:databases/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:databases/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:databases/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:databases/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:databases/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:databases/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:databases/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:databases/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:databases/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:databases/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:databases/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:databases/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:databases/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:databases/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:databases/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:databases/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:databases/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:databases/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:databases/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:databases/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:databases/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:databases/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:databases/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:databases/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:databases/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:databases/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:databases/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:databases/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:databases/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:databases/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:databases/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:databases/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:databases/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:databases/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:databases/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:databases/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] Like most other relational database products, PostgreSQL supports *aggregate functions*.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] An aggregate function computes a single result from multiple input rows.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] For example, there are aggregates to compute the `count`, `sum`, `avg` (average), `max` (maximum) and `min` (minimum) over a set of rows.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] but this will not work since the aggregate `max` cannot be used in the `WHERE` clause.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] This is OK because the subquery is an independent computation that computes its own aggregate separately from what is happening in the outer query.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] Aggregates are also very useful in combination with `GROUP BY` clauses.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] Each aggregate result is computed over the table rows matching that city.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] which gives us the same results for only the cities that have all `temp_lo` values below 40.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] It is important to understand the interaction between aggregates and SQL's `WHERE` and `HAVING` clauses.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] The fundamental difference between `WHERE` and `HAVING` is this: `WHERE` selects input rows before groups and aggregates are computed (thus, it controls which rows go into the aggregate computation), whereas `HAVING` selects group rows after groups and aggregates are computed.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] Thus, the `WHERE` clause must not contain aggregate functions; it makes no sense to try to use an aggregate to determine which rows will be inputs to the aggregates.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] On the other hand, the `HAVING` clause always contains aggregate functions.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] (Strictly speaking, you are allowed to write a `HAVING` clause that doesn't use aggregates, but it's seldom useful.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] In the previous example, we can apply the city name restriction in `WHERE`, since it needs no aggregate.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] This is more efficient than adding the restriction to `HAVING`, because we avoid doing the grouping and aggregate calculations for all rows that fail the `WHERE` check.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] `FILTER` is much like `WHERE`, except that it removes rows only from the input of the particular aggregate function that it is attached to.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] Here, the `count` aggregate counts only rows with `temp_lo` below 45; but the `max` aggregate is still applied to all rows, so it still finds the reading of 46.
[src:databases/tutorial-agg] If you see anything in the documentation that is not correct, does not match your experience with the particular feature or requires further clarification, please use this form to report a documentation issue.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] Thus far, our queries have only accessed one table at a time.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] Queries can access multiple tables at once, or access the same table in such a way that multiple rows of the table are being processed at the same time.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] Queries that access multiple tables (or multiple instances of the same table) at one time are called *join* queries.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] They combine rows from one table with rows from a second table, with an expression specifying which rows are to be paired.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] Since the columns all had different names, the parser automatically found which table they belong to.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] It is widely considered good style to qualify all column names in a join query, so that the query won't fail if a duplicate column name is later added to one of the tables.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] This syntax pre-dates the `JOIN`/`ON` syntax, which was introduced in SQL-92.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] The tables are simply listed in the `FROM` clause, and the comparison expression is added to the `WHERE` clause.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] The results from this older implicit syntax and the newer explicit `JOIN`/`ON` syntax are identical.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] But for a reader of the query, the explicit syntax makes its meaning easier to understand: The join condition is introduced by its own key word whereas previously the condition was mixed into the `WHERE` clause together with other conditions.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] Now we will figure out how we can get the Hayward records back in.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] What we want the query to do is to scan the `weather` table and for each row to find the matching `cities` row(s).
[src:databases/tutorial-join] If no matching row is found we want some “empty values” to be substituted for the `cities` table's columns.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] This kind of query is called an *outer join*.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] This query is called a *left outer join* because the table mentioned on the left of the join operator will have each of its rows in the output at least once, whereas the table on the right will only have those rows output that match some row of the left table.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] When outputting a left-table row for which there is no right-table match, empty (null) values are substituted for the right-table columns.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] We can also join a table against itself.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] As an example, suppose we wish to find all the weather records that are in the temperature range of other weather records.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] So we need to compare the `temp_lo` and `temp_hi` columns of each `weather` row to the `temp_lo` and `temp_hi` columns of all other `weather` rows.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] Here we have relabeled the weather table as `w1` and `w2` to be able to distinguish the left and right side of the join.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] You will encounter this style of abbreviating quite frequently.
[src:databases/tutorial-join] The join is usually performed in a more efficient manner than actually comparing each possible pair of rows, but this is invisible to the user.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] To retrieve data from a table, the table is *queried*.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] An SQL `SELECT` statement is used to do this.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] The statement is divided into a select list (the part that lists the columns to be returned), a table list (the part that lists the tables from which to retrieve the data), and an optional qualification (the part that specifies any restrictions).
[src:databases/tutorial-select] You can write expressions, not just simple column references, in the select list.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] Notice how the `AS` clause is used to relabel the output column.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] A query can be “qualified” by adding a `WHERE` clause that specifies which rows are wanted.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] The `WHERE` clause contains a Boolean (truth value) expression, and only rows for which the Boolean expression is true are returned.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] The usual Boolean operators (`AND`, `OR`, and `NOT`) are allowed in the qualification.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] In this example, the sort order isn't fully specified, and so you might get the San Francisco rows in either order.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] Here again, the result row ordering might vary.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] [2] While `SELECT *` is useful for off-the-cuff queries, it is widely considered bad style in production code, since adding a column to the table would change the results.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] [3] In some database systems, including older versions of PostgreSQL, the implementation of `DISTINCT` automatically orders the rows and so `ORDER BY` is unnecessary.
[src:databases/tutorial-select] But this is not required by the SQL standard, and current PostgreSQL does not guarantee that `DISTINCT` causes the rows to be ordered.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] You can enter this into `psql` with the line breaks.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] `psql` will recognize that the command is not terminated until the semicolon.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] White space (i.e., spaces, tabs, and newlines) can be used freely in SQL commands.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] That means you can type the command aligned differently than above, or even all on one line.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] Whatever follows them is ignored up to the end of the line.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] SQL is case-insensitive about key words and identifiers, except when identifiers are double-quoted to preserve the case (not done above).
[src:databases/tutorial-table] `varchar(80)` specifies a data type that can store arbitrary character strings up to 80 characters in length.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] `real` is a type for storing single precision floating-point numbers.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] (Yes, the column of type `date` is also named `date`.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] PostgreSQL supports the standard SQL types `int`, `smallint`, `real`, `double precision`, char(*`N`*), varchar(*`N`*), `date`, `time`, `timestamp`, and `interval`, as well as other types of general utility and a rich set of geometric types.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] PostgreSQL can be customized with an arbitrary number of user-defined data types.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] Consequently, type names are not key words in the syntax, except where required to support special cases in the SQL standard.
[src:databases/tutorial-table] The `point` type is an example of a PostgreSQL-specific data type.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] In databases and transaction processing, **two-phase locking** (**2PL**) is a pessimistic concurrency control method that guarantees conflict-serializability.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] It is also the name of the resulting set of database transaction schedules (histories).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] The protocol uses locks, applied by a transaction to data, which may block (interpreted as signals to stop) other transactions from accessing the same data during the transaction's life.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Shrinking phase: locks are released and no locks are acquired.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Two types of locks are used by the basic protocol: *Shared* and *Exclusive* locks.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Refinements of the basic protocol may use more lock types.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Using locks that block processes, 2PL, S2PL, and SS2PL may be subject to deadlocks that result from the mutual blocking of two or more transactions.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Locks are used to guarantee serializability.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] A transaction is *holding* a lock on an object if that transaction has acquired a lock on that object which has not yet been released.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] For 2PL, the only used data-access locks are **read-locks** (**shared locks**) and **write-locks** (**exclusive locks**).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Note that all conflict serializable schedules are also view serializable (but not vice-versa).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] **Shrinking phase** (aka Contracting phase): locks are released and no locks are acquired.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] The two phase locking rules can be summarized as: each transaction must never acquire a lock after it has released a lock.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] The serializability property is guaranteed for a schedule with transactions that obey this rule.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Typically, without explicit knowledge in a transaction on end of phase 1, the rule is safely determined only when a transaction has completed processing and requested commit.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] In this case, all the locks can be released at once (phase 2).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Conservative two-phase locking (C2PL) differs from 2PL in that transactions obtain all the locks they need before the actual execution begins.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] This is to ensure that a transaction that already holds some locks will not block waiting for other locks.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] In cases of heavy lock contention, C2PL reduces the time locks are held on average, relative to 2PL and Strict 2PL, because transactions that hold locks are never blocked.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] In light lock contention, C2PL holds more locks than is necessary, because it is difficult to predict which locks will be needed in the future, thus leading to higher overhead.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] A C2PL transaction will not obtain any locks if it cannot obtain all the locks it needs in its initial request.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Furthermore, each transaction needs to declare its read and write set (the data items that will be read/written), which is not always possible.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Because of these limitations, C2PL is not used very frequently.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] To comply with the strict two-phase locking (S2PL) protocol, a transaction needs to comply with 2PL, and release its *write (exclusive)* locks only after the transaction has ended (i.e., either *committed* or *aborted*).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] On the other hand, *read (shared)* locks are released regularly during the shrinking phase.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Unlike 2PL, S2PL provides strictness (a special case of cascade-less recoverability).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] This protocol is not appropriate in B-trees because it causes Bottleneck (while B-trees always starts searching from the parent root).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] To comply with **strong strict two-phase locking** (SS2PL), a transaction's read and write locks are released only after that transaction has ended (i.e., either committed or aborted).
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] A transaction obeying SS2PL has only a phase 1 and lacks a phase 2 until the transaction has completed.
[src:databases/two-phase-locking] Every SS2PL schedule is also an S2PL schedule, but not vice versa.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] In computer science, **write-ahead logging** (**WAL**) is a family of techniques for providing atomicity and durability (two of the ACID properties) in database systems.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] A write ahead log is an append-only auxiliary disk-resident structure used for crash and transaction recovery.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] The changes are first recorded in the log, which must be written to stable storage, before the changes are written to the database.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] In a system using WAL, all modifications are written to a log before they are applied.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] Usually both redo and undo information is stored in the log.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] The purpose of this can be illustrated by an example.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] Imagine a program that is in the middle of performing some operation when the machine it is running on loses power.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] Upon restart, that program might need to know whether the operation it was performing succeeded, succeeded partially, or failed.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] If a write-ahead log is used, the program can check this log and compare what it was supposed to be doing when it unexpectedly lost power to what was actually done.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] On the basis of this comparison, the program could decide to undo what it had started, complete what it had started, or keep things as they are.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] After a certain number of operations, the program should perform a checkpoint, writing all the changes specified in the WAL to the database and clearing the log.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] WAL allows updates of a database to be done in-place.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] Another way to implement atomic updates is with shadow paging, which is not in-place.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] The main advantage of doing updates in-place is that it reduces the need to modify indexes and block lists.
[src:databases/write-ahead-logging] Modern file systems typically use a variant of WAL for at least file system metadata; this is called journaling.
